<br>
Like the song of the Sirens, Hades could do nothing but comply.  And so he flew, intangibly, up towards consciousness, up towards his love.  But as he approached consciousness, something dark and heavy prevented his return.  As hard as he tried, pushing against this phantasmal force, Hades could not return.<br>
<br>
On the verge of panic, Hades struggled, like a person fighting for the last breath of air before drowning.  But the invisible power pushed back just as hard, forcing Hades back down.<br>
But Hades wouldn't be denied.  With a last desperate lunge, Hades tore free.  Yet something had gone wrong.  <br>
<br>
After the sudden glare that had erupted from the struggle, Hades looked around.  He could see his Persephone, cradling his head, while gently feeding him ambrosia.  But he also saw his body, lying lifeless and still upon the floor.  He stared at himself, and realized that he had become what his kingdom was based upon.  He had become a bodiless soul, weightless and gossamyr-like, wafting upon some unseen breeze.  Shocked and terrified, he tried to call out, and realized he had no voice.  He then tried to re-enter his body, and realized he was barred from doing so.  <br>
<br>
He had in essence become a wraith, voiceless, and powerless, forced to watch things that unfold around him, incapable of doing anything in return.  Filled with anger and the overwhelming sense of futility, Hades screamed a voiceless, unfulfilled scream.<br>
